==Aftermath==
[[Henry Kissinger]] observed in his Vietnam War memoir that the [[Gerald Ford|Ford Administration]] was astonished and shamed by the fact that top Cambodian officials refused to leave the country. These included Premier [[Long Boret]] and [[Lon Non]], the Prime Minister's brother, both of whom were on the Khmer Rouge's advertised death list.<ref>"Encyclopedia of the Vietnam War". ed. Spencer Tucker, s.v. "EAGLE PULL, Operation"</ref>

On 17 April 1975 the Khmer Rouge entered Phnom Penh bringing the [[Cambodian Civil War]] to an end. Long Boret, Lon Non and other top officials of the Khmer Republic Government were executed at the [[Cercle Sportif]], while FANK troops in the city were disarmed, taken to the [[Phnom Penh National Olympic Stadium|Olympic Stadium]] and executed.<ref>{{cite book |title=When The War Was Over Cambodia and the Khmer Rouge Revolution|last=Becker |first=Elizabeth |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=1988 |isbn=1-891620-00-2 |page=160}}</ref>

For 2nd Battalion 4th Marines and Amphibious Ready Group Alpha, Operation Eagle Pull served as a small-scale dress rehearsal for the more complex Operation Frequent Wind 17 days later.<ref name=Dunham/>{{rp|124}}

==In popular culture==
Operation Eagle Pull is depicted in the film [[The Killing Fields (film)|"The Killing Fields"]].

